  Volume                   = {6},

  Annote                   = {Ground penetrating radar (GPR) systems typically
 operate in an electromagnetic near field regime
 where the distance between the GPR antenna and the
 structures of interest are a few wavelengths
 only. Here, the electromagnetic fields of a
 radiating structure (GPR antenna) are not yet plane,
 transverse-electric-magnetic (TEM) waves as in the
 far-field of the antenna. Full wave solutions of the
 propagation effects are thus of particular This
 model should include the geometry of the radiating
 antennas, a portion of the air space over the GPR
 and, most importantly, a flexible parameterization
 of the subsurface under the GPR. Recently, GPR
 configurationas have been analyzed numerically using
 the finite difference time domin (FDTD) scheme. The
 standard FDTD method is viable if the structures of
 interest in the CoD are commensurate. It becomes
 inefficient if the structures must be modeled with a
 variable level of detail. We analyze numerical
 models of simplified GPR measurement setups and
 comment on their relevance for field work.}
}



