  Annote                   = {Ground penetrating radar (GPR) systems typically
 operate in an electromagnetic near field regime
 where the distance between the GPR antenna and the
 structures of interest are a few wavelengths
 only. Full wave solutions of the propagation effects
 are thus of particular interest for the quantitative
 analysis of measured radargrams. Recently, GPR
 configurationas have been analyzed numerically using
 the finite difference time domin (FDTD) scheme. The
 standard FDTD method is viable if the structures of
 interest in the computational domain are
 commensurate. It becomes inefficient if the
 structures must be modeled with a variable level of
 detail. There is therefore a definite need to have a
 computational scheme for the solution of Maxwell´s
 equations in the time doman which is flexible and
 general enough to model geometrical details of
 varying degree of fineness. We investigate a finite
 element time domain (FETD) scheme for the full-wave
 analysis of GPR and report on its performance with
 respect to flexibility and accuracy.}
}

